## STEP 2 — Authorization Gate (Bessie chat workflow)

We insert three nodes between the Chat Trigger and the AI Agent. Nothing about the AI Agent or Tool 6 changes.

**Target shape:**

```
[When chat message received] → [Get Users] → [Authorize User] → [IF Authorized]
                                                                   ├─ true  → [AI Agent]  (existing)
                                                                   └─ false → [Deny Response]
```

### 2.1 Node: "Get Users" (Google Sheets)

1. Open **Bessie - SFA Chat Agent**. Click the connection line between **When chat message received** and **AI Agent** — a small **+** appears; click it and search **Google Sheets**.
2. Configure:

| Setting | Value |
|---|---|
| Credential | your existing "Google Drive account" (same Google account works for Sheets) |
| Resource | Sheet Within Document |
| Operation | Get Row(s) |
| Document | From list → **Bessie_Config** |
| Sheet | From list → **Users** |
| (Filters) | leave empty — return all rows |

3. Rename the node to exactly **`Get Users`** (double-click its title).
4. Settings tab → **Always Output Data: ON**.

> **Why read the sheet every run instead of caching?** At your volume (a handful of runs a day) a sheet read adds ~1 second and zero token cost. Caching (15-min TTL in workflow static data) is a documented Phase 1 optimization — skipping it now keeps this step simple and the behavior easy to reason about. Trade-off acknowledged deliberately.

### 2.2 Node: "Authorize User" (Code)

1. Add a **Code** node after Get Users. Rename it exactly **`Authorize User`**.
2. Paste the full contents of **`code/auth-user.js`** (delivered with this guide).
3. What the code does, in plain English: it takes the rows from Get Users, looks for the current user's ID with `active = TRUE`, maps their role to a list of allowed request types, and outputs either `authorized: true` (plus the original chat message, passed through) or `authorized: false` with a polite denial message. The user ID is currently a fixed value `n8n-chat-default` because the n8n chat window doesn't identify individual people — the chat is already protected by your n8n login. The code has a clearly marked single line to swap when Teams (which *does* send real user IDs) becomes the interface.

### 2.3 Node: "IF Authorized" (IF)

1. Add an **IF** node after Authorize User. Rename it **`IF Authorized`**.
2. Condition: **Boolean** → Value 1: `={{ $json.authorized }}` → is **true**.
3. Connect the **true** output to the existing **AI Agent** node.
4. **Important — AI Agent input mapping:** the AI Agent previously received `chatInput` directly from the trigger. It now receives it via the gate. Open the AI Agent node; if its "Text" / prompt source field references the trigger, change it to: `={{ $json.chatInput }}` (the Authorize User node passes `chatInput` through untouched).

### 2.4 Node: "Deny Response" (Set)

1. From **IF Authorized**'s **false** output, add a **Set** node named **`Deny Response`**.
2. Add one string field: name `output`, value `={{ $json.denialMessage }}`.
3. This ends the false branch — the chat shows the denial text and no LLM was ever called (zero token cost for unauthorized requests — a Phase 0 governance and cost win in one).

### ✅ Step 2 verification

1. **Accomplished:** every chat message passes an authorization check before the AI runs.
2. **Verify (positive):** chat "hello" → Bessie replies normally. In the execution log you should see Get Users → Authorize User → IF (true) → AI Agent.
3. **Verify (negative):** in the Users sheet, set the `active` cell to `FALSE`. Chat "hello" again → you should get the "Access denied…" message and the execution log must show **no** AI Agent / Anthropic call. **Set it back to TRUE afterwards.**
4. **Expected output:** normal Bessie behavior when authorized; instant polite refusal when not.
5. **Troubleshooting:** *"Sheet not found"* → tab name has a space. *AI Agent gets empty input* → its prompt field still points at the trigger; change to `{{ $json.chatInput }}` per 2.3.4.
6. **Next:** the audit log — so that every authorized run leaves a permanent trace.

